1588084317878<//date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Text>
Blest to experience the cross here with an ocean view in front of it.

You may want to look into your heart and breathe in the history there.  As you look off to the islands, imagine the Chumash people would look pensively for the canoes to return with abalone, urchin, and fish for the villages below.

The harbors that have been cut for boats for many reasons.  Fisherman, oil from dereks that were strewn out all over below.  And merchants from around the world.

If your mind is clear, and your heart open, the energy there will guide your eyes to see what was and is still today.<//Text>

<Text>Super cute and trendy coffee shop and cafe. Very friendly and welcoming staff. Didn‚Äôt try the food, but the baked goods looked delicious. Got a cappuccino. It‚Äôs served in a satisfyingly heavy glass. The milk was perfectly pulled with velvety micro foam. The shot left something to be desired. I forgot to check where their beans are from, but I wasn‚Äôt impressed. It tastes very lightly of milk chocolate with a slight tang, but without the accompanying fruitiness I expect with a lighter roast. The finish tasted like old, wet grounds. None of the toffee or nuttiness I like in a darker roast, but also none of the more herbal notes you get from a tangier espresso.
There‚Äôs a nice little seating area in the back, but it‚Äôs better for a brunch date than to work on a screenplay.
Solid third wave coffee with hopefully just a bad day on the espresso machine.<//Text><Rating>4</Rating><user_id>108131807922403699217</user_id>< GmapID>

< date>
1578175274515<//date>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<text>This location is small, but they have seating both inside and outside. The lattes were quite good, albeit a bit small. < text>
I write for a music and coffee blog called Crooners In Coffeeshops, in which I interview local musicians at local coffeeshops. My writeup reflects the positive experience that I encountered at Go Get Em Tiger on our interview date.

Go Get ‚ÄòEm Tiger has come to be known as a beloved L.A coffee chain with roots in many foot traffic heavy neighborhoods. Opened in 2018, the Highland Park location found a home in a cute little small business cul-de-sac style building on the illustrious Figueroa Street, accompanied by Triple Beam Pizza and Highland Park Wine. Sound the alarm! You can get coffee, pizza AND wine in the the same hub!

Anyways, due to sharing a space with other businesses, GGET HP‚Äôs shop size is a bit smaller than some of their other locations, but that‚Äôs not to say that they don‚Äôt utilize their space to its fullest potential. A clean color palette of white and their signature light blue paired with luscious green plants hanging from the ceiling and light, warm wood display shelves (which also include plants and coffee making items). Plus, they have a cute indoor patio area for happy customers to enjoy their delicious coffee and healthy noms (if they don‚Äôt want pizza of course). All in all, the GGET team has done it again with a lovely location for locals to enjoy.<//text>

< text>
Really dig this place for working. They've got free, passwordless wifi, great coffee, and ample seating. I'll note that the seating isn't entirely indoors which, because it's LA, is totally fine almost all of the time. There were a couple days this summer that I found myself pretty warm and I can imagine it gets chilly in the winter, but I'm not one to complain about our almost perfect weather in Southern California. The space is shared with Triple Beam (my favorite pizza in LA) and Hippo--also just a very hip part of HLP.

I usually just stick with the coffee and cold brew here, both of which I like. I've gotten the Business & Pleasure one as well which has three little fun coffee and tea drinks, but honestly is maybe overkill for my needs. They've got some breakfast-y foods that I haven't tried (because pizza), but it's nice to know they're available. Parking is easy and free on the side streets off Figueroa. Lovely addition to the neighborhood!</text>

A must go. Beautiful sight. Little graffiti. Everyone is friendly. Hike, bike, motorcycle or 4x4. 2 wheel drive will be tough/not make it in many sections and I highly recommend no trying. There is a gate that can be locked so if you drive/motorcycle up there is a chance you can locked in or out so prepare your trip. If it rained the gate is usually locked for several days after.</Review>

<user>113280385154916365255< /user>< name>
Oscar Trask</name>
<time>1550850104155< /time><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
We took the Funicular up to the top, we queued for approx 20-30mins for tickets and to get on. Not many people can fit on the train, hence the queues. But the fastest way to the top (5mins). Once at the top, greeted by wonderful views, couple of souvenir shops also. We then walked up to the white Mary statue. We then decided to walk back down to the city. Took us approx 1hr. Nice walk, passing a large outdoor swimming pool also.< /review>

<time>1513722674315< /time><Rating>5</Rating>< text>
It's the top of a mountain....it's tall and good looking...but be careful....it can hurt you.</text>
< Pics>
None<//Pics>
<Response>None< /Response>< gmap_id>
0x80dcbfe3a4cf330b:0x5bd716638671c4cd< /gmap_id>
</record></dataset><record>
<Name>John Murphy</Name>< text>
A short walk from our hotel was the Parque Metropolitano, which is better known as the Cerro San Cristobal. This is Santiago's largest open, green space and, at is summit is a gleaming white statue (just under 50 feet tall) of the Vergen de la Immaculada Concepcion. There are three ways to approach the summit. One way is to walk along roads, which are more fitted for cars and walkers, the second a steep, dirt trail and the third is by the funicular from Plaza Caupolican. At times this can get rather busy but, in our opinion, it still worth undergoing the "Disney-like snake" queues to use this way to reach the top. At the top, apart from the statue itself, there are benches at its feet which form the outdoor church where Pope John Paul II celebrated mass in 1984. The summit should be a place for quiet contemplation but, for us, it was slightly spoilt by the canned music playing through the speakers dotted round the summit. This apart, a trip to the top is well worth a detour not only for the place itself but also for the views of Santiago laid out model-village like at your feet.<//text>

<review>What a wonderful experience at PPD. I have had a dentist phobia since I was 6 years old (terrible, traumatizing experiences as a kid because my parents didn't prioritize finding the *right* dentist so I had to be strapped in with restraints) so I came in very apprehensive, scared and already triggered by the sounds.

But! Everyone on the staff were so understanding, empathetic, and warm from the get-go. They understood my fears, listened to me, and were wonderful from the exams, to the x-rays, to the cleaning and everything in between. It's really helped assuage my fear of the dentist! <name>smhg2019< /name>< Text>
I very much wanted to write a great review of this place!  I loved it when I started there a year ago.  I really respected my doctor, Dr. Chang, and I had a great experience with the dental hygienist too.  However, this place is one of several practices under the same management, and they recently had a full turnover of front-end staff and doctors.  I am in the middle of some orthodontic work, and apparently, the office lost all the retainer impressions and past records from my doctor when she left.  The new office manager is extremely unhelpful, patronizing and borderline rude.  So, my teeth are now shifting and my bite is regressing after paying $6000 out of pocket!  I have to start all over again. This is NOT a family dental practice.  It is a corporate one and the dentists and specialist on staff rotate between this office and several others.  This seems to be an overall trend in the dental industry and a very unfortunate one.  I can not, in good conscience, recommend this place.< /Text>

< Review>
I very much wanted to write a great review of this place!  I loved it when I started there a year ago.  I really respected my doctor, Dr. Chang, and I had a great experience with the dental hygienist too.  However, this place is one of several practices under the same management, and they recently had a full turnover of front-end staff and doctors. <review>Awesome vegan restaurant that is close to the water - Oceanside pier.  You can order your food inside or call it in.  We happened to go on a Thursday late afternoon before the dinner rush and we had the place to ourselves.

The food is thoughtfully prepared and served with the waiter wearing a mask all of the time. We used the outside dining area which was cozy.  I tried the super veggie burrito and my wife had the YIPPEE-KI-YAY burger with their pretzel bun.  Both items were filling and tasted freshly prepared. It was great to enjoy a completely vegan meal in a kitchen that prepares all plant based meals.

Enjoy eating plants...<//review>< Pics>

When I think vegan I typically think bland and boring, but I've transformed haha. Eve Oceanside is delicious and delightful and we can't wait to go back and experience more of the delicious(and healthy) menu. Decided to give them a try last night for our anniversary dinner, being that we've been fasting from meat & wheat for a few weeks, this place was like hitting the jackpotüôå. We ordered the Seitan Pepperoni & Olive flatbread, Peppadew Pesto Flatbread and Southern Mystic bowl and were very impressed with the melding of flavors with all our choices. < Text>
Unprofessional customer service highlighted a visit that should have ended with a care sale. Instead the finale was highlighted by a ride home in my old car, laughing about the experience I will never forget.

Scams attempted: (in order of appearance)

1. Price of vehicle shown online didn't match Paper price. Made an obvious lie saying it was a mistake to cover for an attempt at hoping I was a negligent buyer. (warranty declinedat this point see below)

2. Initial finance data provided no break down. Only showed Monthly payment. I had to ask 3 times for a break down. They would not provide data on what financial institution was providing the loan. Sketchy as all what not tactics are a reoccurring theme.

2. Fake fees tacked on. Including a "weight fee" that magically brought the vehicle back up to the sticker price.

3. Inflated taxes. Which magically disappeared when I pointed out the math wasn't adding up.

4. The manager arrival technique. Without my prompting the sales person brought in the original data absent paperwork, and attempted to comment about the "great price" and how "cool" the car was. I had to ask again for a line item breakdown of costs, taxes, fees and whatever else was included in the final price.

5. The alarm is optional and you need it because people use their phones to steal cars these days scam. Let's all just apply common sense to this one.

6. The extended warranty brought back into price, even though I declined it at outset.

Other highlights:

The test drive was an education session for the... wait for it... sales associate who knew nothing about the car. If you don't know what you are trying to sell, people who deal in research like me will see right through your ruse.

I made a fair cash offer, and I mean fair. Which, because they weren't getting an in house finance they kept avoiding, and pushing the financing. a comment made at least three times. "Just finance it and you can pay it off early. there's no early termination fee, it doesn't hurt at all." Common sense people... will take you far. That is of course if mathematical analysis and simple interest formulas are part of your common culture.

When i made the cash offer, and said final offer or ill walk. they pushed financing again, which at this point is blatant rude bordering harassment, then proceeded to follow me outside to push it a final time.

This dealer is the real deal, if the deal you are looking for is an experience with how horrible dealership experiences can be.< /Text>

<text>I had been shopping for a Tacoma for a couple of months. I had contacted Claremont Toyota early on in my search as I had purchased a vehicle from them prior and was happy with the transaction. I made contact with Derrick Bates. He checked the stock and told me that they did not have one equipped as I wanted. Derrick mentioned that he would keep an eye out for one like I was looking for.

I continued my shopping. I contacted numerous dealers who said they had one like I was looking for. After going to the dealers and seeing that they were either just telling me they had one and then trying to replace it with something different or they inflated the price so high that the sale was ridiculous I was getting really burned out and was ready to just wait a few months.

Derrick contacted me as he had followed through on his promise to look for a vehicle for me. He said he had one in transit that would be the one I was looking for. <user>110600388534213109083<//user><Name>Ryan Quinn<//Name><time>1468986694713< /time><Rate>2< /Rate>< Review>
My experience at Claremont  Toyota which will be listed was a largely negative experience. However, I will mention both the good and the bad.

The Good:
The environment was extremely cleanly and all of the lower level staff were extremely polite at all times.
The shuttle service for those seeking to go elsewhere is free and fast.

The bad: I went in for a recalled airbag, I made an appointment, showed up and was informed the car part had not arrived  and that they were sorry, sales offered to fill up my tank next time which I accepted. The repair takes 6 hours although I am initially told 4.  My shuttle back is an uncomfortable half hour listening to (not my choice) conservative talk radio and hearing the driver tell me how great Donald Trump is.

When I inquired over the delay management bristled, insisting that this is "normal" that an appointment didn't really mean you would get your car repairs would get started but was an arbitrary placeholder.  When I went to sales (as the service manager had left for the day) I was sold a barnyard variety of excuses. Rather than anything resembling accountability.

Bottom Line:  I did not take the gasoline.  They are untrustworthy and unprofessional. These are not traits I seek in my mechanic, or my car dealer.< /Review>
